</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C351651EFF8AEE6EFF16FF20F23F2BEB" pageId="24" pageNumber="23" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BF43695FF8AEE6EFF16FF20F23F2BEB" blockId="24.[192,1440,200,251]" pageId="24" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis id="B93FEA87FF8AEE6EFF16FF20F0532BCB" bold="true" box="[192,352,200,219]" pageId="24" pageNumber="23">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name results from the combination of the genus name 
<taxonomicName id="4C4B4D16FF8AEE6EFB92FF20F5DE2BCB" authorityName="Reitter" authorityYear="1892" box="[1092,1261,200,219]" class="Insecta" family="Aphodiidae" genus="Gonaphodius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93FEA87FF8AEE6EFB92FF20F5DE2BCB" box="[1092,1261,200,219]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="23">Gonaphodius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the suffix – 
<emphasis id="B93FEA87FF8AEE6EFF06FF00F0232BEB" box="[208,272,232,251]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="23">opsis</emphasis>
[= looking like]. The gender is feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C351651EFF8AEE6EFF16FEC0F2C92A4B" pageId="24" pageNumber="23" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BF43695FF8AEE6EFF16FEC0F2C92A4B" blockId="24.[192,1440,296,347]" pageId="24" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis id="B93FEA87FF8AEE6EFF16FEC0F06C2A2B" bold="true" box="[192,351,296,315]" pageId="24" pageNumber="23">Bionomics.</emphasis>
Besides the species collected in horse or sheep dung in open pastures or in forests, several taxa were found feeding in bat dung in caves (labels data).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
